dex=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Getting Certified</span><hr size=1> Jimmy T.,<br>
     Thanks for the welcome. I really worked hard preparing to get certified. First, I ordered the video and study guide from Federation of Fly Fishers in Montana. Look on their Web site. This is key. Most of the questions and nearly all the demonstration parts of the test ( 2 part test) come from the study guide and video. You can also get a print out of the casting part of the test off the web. Then I read from cover to cover and hilighted Mel Krieger's, Joan Wolff's, and Lefty Kreh's books and then went back over the highlight's. (not absolutely necessary but it did help fill in some blanks I didn't fully understand after reading the FFF material). I also bought Mel Krieger's and Doug Swisher's advanced videos and studied them until my wife threatened to strangle me. She said she knew I had to have them memorized because she certainly did. Then I practiced and practiced and practiced some more almost every day and sometimes twice a day for about 6 months in my front yard. I would like to have 5 dollars for every car that drove by and asked &quot;are you catching anything.&quot;<br>
Then when I thought I was getting close I called Allen Crise in Texas (a well known and very competent fly casting instructor) and made an appointment for a half day lesson, to fine tune me.It was well worth the 6 hour drive one way. Al and I went through the whole demonstration part of the test step by step. He picked up a fault I had (rolling my wrist which was causing my casts to curve) which I had been having trouble with for years and was killing my accuracy that I would never have picked up  on my own. He also got my backcast up higher which he said the testers, Chuck Easterling and Art Mazzier would nail me for if I didn't correct. Jimmy, I don't know where you live but if you are thinking about testing and you're in Arkansas, I reccomend talking to Chuck (if he can help you since he's a tester ) or John Wilson. I've seen John cast and he is very good and has been certified for a long time.<br>
     Even if you don't pass the first time, the process is priceless. Good luck and let me know if I can help you.<br>
<br>
                                       Robert McMahan <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flynut62>flynut62</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#000000>(8/28/03 5:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=147.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Getting Certified</span><hr size=1> When is Maddogs fish in ??? Is the the one on Fly Anglers Online?<br>
